\begin_layout Subsection
Payroll Apportionment (fixed wage)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Under 100% payroll apportionment of corporate taxes, the optimization condition
 of the firm can be re-expressed as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\underset{p_{1},p_{2},l_{1},l_{2}}{\max}\left(1-\frac{w_{1}\ell_{1}}{w_{1}\ell_{1}+w_{2}\ell_{2}}t_{1}-\frac{w_{2}\ell_{2}}{w_{1}\ell_{1}+w_{2}\ell_{2}}t_{2}\right)\left(\kappa_{1}p_{1}^{1-\varepsilon_{1}}-w_{1}\ell_{1}+\kappa_{2}p_{2}^{1-\varepsilon_{2}}-w_{2}\ell_{2}\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 subject to 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\kappa_{1}p_{1}^{-\varepsilon_{1}}+\kappa_{2}p_{2}^{-\varepsilon_{2}}=\ell_{1}^{\alpha}+\ell_{2}^{\alpha}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

We solve numerically as above.
 As can be seen in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:payroll"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, prices and quantities remain constant as under separate accounting, while
 labour is shifted to the low-tax region.
