\begin_layout Subsection
Payroll Apportionment (monopsony)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose that instead of a fixed wage 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{i}$
\end_inset

 in each region, the firm chooses the wage and faces a labour supply curve
 of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell_{i}\left(w_{i}\right)=cw_{i}^{\rho}$
\end_inset

.
 It then solves the problem 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\underset{p_{1},p_{2},w_{1},w_{2}}{\max}\left(1-\frac{w_{1}\ell_{1}}{w_{1}\ell_{1}+w_{2}\ell_{2}}t_{1}-\frac{w_{2}\ell_{2}}{w_{1}\ell_{1}+w_{2}\ell_{2}}t_{2}\right)\left(\kappa_{1}p_{1}^{1-\varepsilon_{1}}-w_{1}\ell_{1}+\kappa_{2}p_{2}^{1-\varepsilon_{2}}-w_{2}\ell_{2}\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 subject to 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{1}p_{1}^{-\varepsilon_{1}}+\kappa_{2}p_{2}^{-\varepsilon_{2}}=\ell_{1}^{\alpha}+\ell_{2}^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell_{i}\left(w_{i}\right)=cw_{i}^{\rho}\iff\left(\frac{\ell_{i}}{c}\right)^{\frac{1}{\rho}}=w_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 We set labour supply elasticity, 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho=3$
\end_inset

, and calibrate 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 so that price levels are equal to those under separate accounting when
 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{1}=t_{2}=0.2$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly to when wages were fixed, relative prices and quantities are
 equal across regions, with labour decreasing as tax rates increase.
 However, we can also see that wages fall in region 1 and rise in region
 2 as the tax rate rises.
 
